Florida has a long list of offenses that are ineligible for court-ordered sealing or expunction when the record is a
conviction
for one of those offenses. Important Florida nuance: for 943.0584,
conviction
includes a guilty/no-contest plea or determination of guilt even if adjudication is withheld. ("https://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0900-0999%2F0943%2FSections%2F0943.0584.html")
Wilma should flag likely ineligible/manual review for:
sexual misconduct;
illegal explosives;
terrorism;
murder, manslaughter, homicide;
domestic assault/battery;
aggravated assault;
felony battery, domestic battery by strangulation, aggravated battery;
stalking/aggravated stalking;
luring or enticing a child;
human trafficking as a charged offense under the barred-offense list, unless the user is the trafficking victim seeking the separate victim route;
kidnapping/false imprisonment;
chapter 794 sexual offenses;
lewd/lascivious offenses involving minors;
arson;
burglary of a dwelling;
voyeurism/digital voyeurism;
robbery, carjacking, home-invasion robbery;
Florida Communications Fraud Act violations;
elderly/disabled adult abuse;
child abuse/aggravated child abuse;
sexual performance by a child;
public-corruption offenses under chapter 839;
certain obscenity/computer sex crimes;
selling/buying minors;
aircraft piracy;
manufacturing controlled substances;
drug trafficking;
any predicate offense for sexual predator or sexual offender registration. ("https://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0900-0999%2F0943%2FSections%2F0943.0584.html")
Wilma rule: If a user says
the judge withheld adjudication,
do not assume eligibility. For 943.0584 listed offenses, a guilty/no-contest plea or finding can still block relief even when adjudication was withheld.

Florida has a special expunction route for lawful self-defense cases. It applies when the State Attorney or Statewide Prosecutor certifies that no charge was filed, or the charge was dismissed by the prosecutor or court, because the person acted in lawful self-defense under Floridas justifiable-use-of-force law. ("https://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0900-0999%2F0943%2FSections%2F0943.0578.html")
Wilma must confirm:
the case involved self-defense;
no charging document was filed, or the charge was dismissed;
dismissal/no-file was because of lawful self-defense;
prosecutor certification is available;
the user uses the specific lawful self-defense FDLE process, not the normal expunction packet. FDLE warns not to use this application for other charges or other expunction types. ("https://www.fdle.state.fl.us/seal-and-expunge-process/lawful-self-defense-expungement")

Step 1 - Get the record
Wilma should collect or tell the user to obtain:
FDLE personal review or criminal history;
clerk certified disposition for each charge;
arresting agency name;
arrest date or Notice to Appear date;
charge name and statute;
final disposition;
probation/supervision termination proof;
diversion completion proof, if applicable.
FDLE says a Personal Review lets a person examine their Florida criminal history for accuracy and completeness and is generally used to determine which arrest dates may be eligible. FDLE states no charge is assessed for that personal review service. ("https://www.fdle.state.fl.us/seal-and-expunge-process/frequently-asked-questions")
Step 2 - Determine route
Use outcome-first logic:
no charge/dismissal/acquittal expunction check;
withhold sealing check;
adjudicated guilty usually ineligible for normal route;
trafficking/self-defense/juvenile/mistaken arrest special route check.
Step 3 - Apply to FDLE
For normal sealing/expunction, the user submits the FDLE Certificate of Eligibility application with certified disposition, fingerprints, notarized signature, and $75 fee. Expunction also requires the prosecutor certified-statement page. ("https://www.fdle.state.fl.us/seal-and-expunge-process/certificate-of-eligibility-instructions")
Step 4 - File in court
After FDLE issues the certificate, the user files the petition, sworn statement/affidavit, certificate, and proposed order in the court with jurisdiction over the arrest, usually the county where the arrest occurred. FDLE says the certificate is not the final step and does not guarantee sealing or expunction. ("https://www.fdle.state.fl.us/seal-and-expunge-process/frequently-asked-questions")
Step 5 - Serve required parties
The petition must be served on the appropriate State Attorney or Statewide Prosecutor and the arresting agency. The State and arresting agency may respond. ("https://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0900-0999%2F0943%2FSections%2F0943.0585.html")
Step 6 - Order distribution
If granted, the clerk certifies the order to the State Attorney/Statewide Prosecutor and arresting agency. The arresting agency forwards it to other agencies that received the record, and FDLE forwards the order to the FBI. ("https://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0900-0999%2F0943%2FSections%2F0943.059.html")
